            <p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="1">Not well enough.  I was a telemarketer for several months back in 94-95, and started out around $8/hour, plus a $.25 raise every month as long as I stayed at the top of the room.  This still wasn't enough to compensate for the stress the job caused, and the dickheads on the other end of the line.<br />
<br />
I tried it again when I moved back to Ohio this last March, and lasted 3 days before quitting.  Now the FCC is putting the hammer down on telemarketing so hard, that you can't even breath too loud on the phone without the risk of a fine/jail time/loss of job.<br />
<br />
Plus I can't stand phones.  I've had a few cell phones the last 10 years, and I think I've carried it with me a couple dozen times.  I keep it active, for some unknown reason, but my current phone hasn't even left it's charging cradle for 3 months, or so.<br />
<br />
If I didn't have a child, I wouldn't have a home phone, either.  I just keep it now incase of an emergency (poison control, EMT, etc).<br />
<br />
But yes, if you request to be taken off their calling list, they are required to do so by order of the FCC.  If the punk has an attitude and reschedules your call or just disregards your request, he will be royaly plugged.  I don't recall if you would be subject to any compensation, or not.<br />
<br />
Keep in mind, though, that the DNC list is only for that particular company.  Removing your name from that single list won't guarantee that you'll never receive another solicitation.  Eventually, though, you should be cleared from the majority of them, if not all.</font></p>
             
